Introduction

Diabetic Retinopathy (DR) is one of the leading causes of blindness worldwide, especially among adults with diabetes. It occurs due to damage to the blood vessels in the retina caused by prolonged high blood sugar levels. Early detection and treatment of DR are crucial to prevent vision loss. However, diagnosing DR typically requires skilled ophthalmologists and specialized equipment, which may not be accessible in remote or underserved regions.

With the advent of deep learning and computer vision, automated solutions for DR detection have gained attention. The Diabetic Retinopathy Resized Dataset, available on Kaggle, provides high-resolution retinal images labeled with different levels of DR severity, enabling researchers to train machine learning models for automated diagnosis. This project leverages the dataset to develop a robust AI-based system for detecting and classifying diabetic retinopathy, potentially supporting early diagnosis and improving patient outcomes.

Reference to the datafile https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/tanlikesmath/diabetic-retinopathy-resized/data

Other References :

  • https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diabetic_retinopathy
  • https://www.kaggle.com/c/diabetic-retinopathy-detection
  • chatgpt

Project Goal

The goal of this project is to develop a deep learning-based system for automated diabetic retinopathy detection using the VGG16 pre-trained model. By leveraging transfer learning, the project focuses on:

  1. Image Classification:

    • Classifying retinal images into different stages of diabetic retinopathy based on the severity levels defined in the dataset.

  2. Optimization for Accuracy:

    • Fine-tuning the VGG16 architecture to maximize classification accuracy while balancing sensitivity and specificity, ensuring clinically relevant results.

  3. Preprocessing and Augmentation:

    • Implementing data augmentation techniques for improved generalization and handling the imbalanced distribution of classes within the dataset.

  4. Evaluation:

    • Validating the trained model using metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and AUC-ROC to ensure robust performance.

  5. Deployment Feasibility:

    • Designing a scalable and efficient model architecture suitable for integration into healthcare applications, including real-time deployment for early DR screening.

Use Cases

  1. Automated Screening Tool:

    • Use the trained model as a screening tool for early detection of diabetic retinopathy, reducing the workload on ophthalmologists and enabling early interventions.

  2. Telemedicine Integration:

    • Deploy the model in telemedicine platforms for remote diagnosis, especially in rural or underserved areas where access to specialists is limited.

  3. Clinical Decision Support:

    • Assist medical professionals by providing a second opinion or initial screening of retinal images to prioritize patients for further examination.

  4. Medical Education and Training:

    • Use the model and dataset to train students and researchers in medical imaging, focusing on how AI can enhance healthcare diagnostics.

  5. Healthcare Research:

    • Utilize the model to analyze patterns in diabetic retinopathy progression, contributing to research on the causes and prevention of DR-related blindness.

  6. Real-Time Screening Applications:

    • Incorporate the trained model into mobile or handheld devices for real-time DR screening during routine check-ups.

  7. Explainable AI in Medicine:

    • Implement Grad-CAM or other visualization techniques to highlight regions of the retina that influence predictions, improving trust and usability for clinicians.

from shutil import copy2
from tqdm import tqdm

# Function to move files
def move_files(dataframe, output_dir):
    for _, row in tqdm(dataframe.iterrows(), total=len(dataframe)):
        src = os.path.join(dataset_dir, row['image'])  # Source file path
        dst = os.path.join(output_dir, f'class_{row["binary_label"]}', row['image'])  # Destination path
        if os.path.exists(src):
            copy2(src, dst)
        else:
            print(f"File not found: {src}")

# Move files for each split
print("Copying training images...")
move_files(train_df, os.path.join(base_output_dir, 'train'))

print("Copying validation images...")
move_files(val_df, os.path.join(base_output_dir, 'validation'))

print("Copying test images...")
move_files(test_df, os.path.join(base_output_dir, 'test'))

print("All files moved.")

In[69]:






# Define directories
train_dir = 'dataset_split/train'
val_dir = 'dataset_split/validation'
test_dir = 'dataset_split/test'

# Define image size and batch size
IMG_SIZE = (224, 224)
BATCH_SIZE = 32

# Define data generators
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1./255,          # Normalize pixel values
    rotation_range=20,       # Augmentations
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True
)

val_test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)  # Only normalize for validation/test

# Load images from directories
train_generator = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    train_dir,
    target_size=IMG_SIZE,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='binary'
)

val_generator = val_test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    val_dir,
    target_size=IMG_SIZE,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='binary'
)

test_generator = val_test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    test_dir,
    target_size=IMG_SIZE,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='binary',
    shuffle=False  # Maintain file order for evaluation
)

In[70]:






# Load the VGG16 model without the top layer
base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(224, 224, 3))

# Freeze the base model layers
for layer in base_model.layers:
    layer.trainable = False

# Add custom layers on top
x = Flatten()(base_model.output)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
output = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)  # Sigmoid for binary classification

# Create the final model
model = Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=output)

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Print model summary
model.summary()

# 2. Compute precision, recall, and F1-score
# Handle undefined metrics with zero_division=1
precision = precision_score(y_true, y_pred, average='weighted', zero_division=1)
recall = recall_score(y_true, y_pred, average='weighted', zero_division=1)
f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_pred, average='weighted', zero_division=1)

# Print the precision, recall, and F1-score

print(f"Recall: {recall:.2f}")
print(f"F1 Score: {f1:.2f}")

# 3. Generate the classification report
print("\nClassification Report:")

Interpretations

  2. Recall:

Key Observations
    

  1. Class Imbalance Issue:
    

      

    • The model performs well for "No Retinopathy" but fails for "Retinopathy." This suggests significant class imbalance.
      • 

    

    2. 

  2. Imbalanced Precision and Recall:
    

      

    • Precision for "Retinopathy" is high but misleading since recall is 0%, indicating failure to detect true cases.
      • 

    

    3. 

  3. Weighted and Macro Averages:
    

      

    • Macro Average: Simple average of metrics across both classes, giving equal weight to all classes.
      • 

    • Weighted Average: Accounts for class support. Dominance of "No Retinopathy" inflates weighted metrics.
      • 

    

    4. 





Suggestions for Improvement
    

  1. Data Balancing:
    

      

    • Use techniques like oversampling (e.g., SMOTE) or undersampling to balance the dataset.
      • 

    

    2. 

  2. Adjust Class Weights:
    

      

    • Assign higher weight to the minority class ("Retinopathy") during training.
      • 

    

    3. 

  3. Model Architecture:
    

      

    • Experiment with more complex architectures or pre-trained models to improve performance.
      • 

    

    4. 

  4. Evaluation Metrics:
    

      

    • Consider AUC-ROC as a metric, which is robust to imbalanced datasets.
      • 

    

    5. 





Conclusion
The model shows high accuracy for "No Retinopathy" but fails to detect "Retinopathy" due to class imbalance. Implementing balancing techniques, adjusting class weights, and revisiting the model architecture can improve performance for the minority class.

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

for i, index in enumerate(misclassified_indices):
    try:
        img_path = file_paths[index]
        if not os.path.exists(img_path):
            print(f"File not found: {img_path}")
            continue
        
        img = plt.imread(img_path)
        plt.subplot(2, 5, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(img)
        plt.axis('off')
        plt.title(f"True: {y_true[index]}, Pred: {y_pred[index]}")
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error loading image {img_path}: {e}")
        continue

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

      • Load the image using a library like matplotlib or Pillow.

      • Display the image alongside its true label (y_true) and predicted label (y_pred).

      • 

    • Error Handling:

Diabetic Retinopathy Detection - Final Summary


Project Overview
This project aimed to develop and evaluate a machine learning model for the binary classification of diabetic retinopathy from retina images. The goal was to classify images into two categories: "No Retinopathy" and "Retinopathy," leveraging deep learning techniques for accurate predictions.

1. Dataset Preparation
    

  • Source: The Kaggle diabetic retinopathy dataset containing resized retina images and corresponding labels.
    • 

  • Preprocessing:
      

    • Normalized file names and ensured alignment with the directory structure.
      • 

    • Split the dataset into training (70%), validation (20%), and test (10%) sets.
      •

    •
